  <sections xmi:id="_SQaWEJaqEeCPtY0LnWkRDw" name="Develop conceptual safety architecture" guid="_SQaWEJaqEeCPtY0LnWkRDw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The conceptual safety architecture is developed so that the functional safety requirements can be allocated to&#xD;
    subsystems.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For detailed guidance on this step refer to ISO 26262, Volume 3 clause 8.4.3.1&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_nVgm4JayEeCPtY0LnWkRDw" name="Optional:- ASIL Decomposition" guid="_nVgm4JayEeCPtY0LnWkRDw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
    The method of ASIL tailoring during the design process given in ISO 26262 is called &quot;ASIL decomposition&quot;. During the&#xD;
    allocation process, benefit can be obtained from architectural decisions and the existence of independent architectural&#xD;
    elements. This offers the opportunity to do the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        implement safety requirements redundantly by these independent architectural elements&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        assign a potentially lower ASIL to these redundant safety requirements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If there is no independence between the elements, the ASIL of the safety goal is inherited by each requirement and&#xD;
    element.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is advised that users refer to ISO 26262, Volume 9, Clause 5 for detailed requirements and guidance on ASIL&#xD;
    decomposition.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_Wx8AgJaqEeCPtY0LnWkRDw" name="Allocate functional safety requirements" guid="_Wx8AgJaqEeCPtY0LnWkRDw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The task of allocating safety requirements to subsystems of the architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The ASIL of the derived safety goal shall be passed to the subsystem.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For detailed guidance on this step refer to ISO 26262, Volume 3 clause 8.4.3.2&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To show the traceability between safety goals, through the safety requirements to the specific subsystems.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The subsystems coming out of the conceptual safety architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
